[3] France (overseas) - Mayotte
Date: Thu 24 Jun 2010
Source: Institut de Veille Sanitaire, Point Epidemiologique no. 46 [in
French, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/regions/reunion_mayotte/pe_rm_deng_46_240610.pdf>


Following an epidemic of dengue in the Comores, the surveillance of
dengue in La Mayotte was stepped-up in March 2010. This surveillance
rested on laboratory virological tests by the CHM (Centre Hospital de
Mayotte). An active research for sick people in the neighborhood was
carried out, highlighting any probable or confirmed cases of dengue
not reported to the agents of the anti-vector (AVL) [campaign], and
tracking the number of suspicious cases seen by physicians in the
sentinel surveillance network, and also in the CHM emergency
department by the monitoring of the distribution of antipyretic drugs
sold by the sentinel network of pharmacies.

As of 23 Jun [2010], the laboratory at the CHM had confirmed 49 cases
of dengue from a total of 666 analyses done since the beginning of
March [2010]. There have been 10 new cases since 9 Jun [2010]. The
number of RT-PCR analyses is about the same [remains stable]. The
total of positives varies, 3.2 percent in [epidemiological] week 24
and 14.3 percent in the preceding week [EW 23].

All the confirmed cases are locally acquired, giving a total of 24
indigenous cases. In addition to the indigenous cases, [there were] 20
imported cases, 3 were lost to followup and 2 are still being checked
[for status] making a total of 49 cases confirmed since March 2010.
The number of probable [suspected] cases is 23: 20 indigenous plus 3
imported. The cases are dispersed all over the island. The 1st group
of cases was at Passamainty in the suburbs and a small cluster of 2
confirmed cases and one probable case in Mtsangamouji.

In [epidemiological] week 24, 3 people with dengue have been
hospitalised, but they have not developed the serious, or hemorrhagic,
form of the disease. Since the start of the circulation of the virus
on the island, no form of the serious fever has been registered .
There have been no deaths.

--
