[5] Honduras
Date: Tue 22 Jun 2010
Source: Tiempo [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Corr. SB, edited]
<http://www.tiempo.hn/web2/editoriales/18259-alarmante-epidemia.html>


The dengue epidemic has spilled over into Honduras and threatens to
decimate our population. It is estimated that one person dies every
day in public hospitals from DHF.

There has been a resurgence of dengue in Central America and some
Latin American countries, due in some measure to the abundance of
rain, but, as far as Honduras is concerned, due to neglect in the
fight against the transmitter of this disease, the mosquito _Aedes
aegypti_.

Dengue in its fatal form, DHF, and classical dengue fever have been
growing rapidly, without the population becoming aware of the danger
of this epidemiological phenomenon. DHF occurs in people who have had
classical dengue fever before.

The Secretariat of Health sees a collapse in its ability to receive
all dengue patients, as there are too many sick people for the
hospital capacity. Accordingly, the government has had no choice but
to hospitalize only those affected with DHF. In view of this
situation, clearly an emergency, it is shown that the public health
system needs the cooperation of the entire population to address this
problem. It also requires the support of the private health care
system, which must adhere to the guidelines established by the
Secretariat of Health.

According to health authorities, the fact that the private health
system has not strictly followed these guidelines for diagnosis, a
product of the experience and expertise of the World Health
Organization (PAHO), has helped to aggravate the situation when
patients finally, in the later stages [of the disease, end up in
public hospitals.

But even with these disadvantages, the key is the attitude of the
majority of Hondurans, who ignore the calls to observe the measures
required to prevent the proliferation of mosquitoes. They do not clean
up weedy areas, avoid water stagnation, or apply insecticides known as
"untadita" of abate [a larvicide], and finally, leave it all to the
goodness of God and action of the government.

In this sense, the initiative of the Secretariat of Health is logical
so that the executive branch decrees a state of health emergency for
the dengue epidemic and a request to municipal governments to apply
coercive means to compel people to observe the measures necessary to
combat the plague of mosquitoes and prevent massive [vector]
infestations throughout the country.

--
